ich microbes (or combinations) are protective, nor whether their absence is the *primary* cause of autoimmune trends or merely a contributing factor.\", \"The studies cited focus on asthma and IBD, but [HY01-E1] notes a rise in *all* autoimmune diseases. The hygiene hypothesis may not generalize across conditions (e.g., ty"}', '2026-02-08 11:44:29.789492');
INSERT INTO public.run_events (id, run_id, seq, event_type, payload_json, created_at) VALUES (171, '8181d748-abd4-46ad-9862-019ded5d86a6', 7, 'agent_message', '{"case_id": "HY01", "model_key": "mistral/mistral-large-latest", "role": "Skeptic", "phase": "independent", "round": 3, "content": "{\"proposed_verdict\": \"INSUFFICIENT\", \"evidence_used\": [\"HY01-E1\", \"HY01-E2\", \"HY01-E3\"], \"key_points\": [\"The hygiene hypothesis (HY01-E1) is correlational: it links rising autoimmune diseases to reduced microbial exposure but does not establish causation. The 3-9% annual increase could coincide with other unmeasured factors (e.g., dietary changes, pollution, sedentary lifestyles).\", \"Farm exposure (HY01-E2) shows strong associations (50% lower asthma, 4x difference in Amish/Hutterite study), but genetic similarity does not rule out confounding variables (e.g., diet, toxin exposure, or other environmental differences beyond microbes).\", \"Antibiotic use and microbiome diversity (HY01-E3) are linked to IBD risk, but this focuses on a subset of autoimmune diseases. The evidence does not address whether microbial exposure is the *primary* driver across all autoimmune conditions or merely a contributing factor.\"], \"uncertainties\": [\"No evidence directly quantifies the proportion of autoimmune disease rise attributable to microbial exposure vs. other factors (e.g., HY01-E1 does not isolate microbial exposure as the dominant cause).\", \"The Amish/Hutterite study (HY01-E2) compares two groups with distinct lifestyles; unmeasured confounders (e.g., stress, diet) could explain the 4x difference, not just microbes.\", \"HY01-E3\\u2019s focus on IBD and antibiotics does not generalize to all autoimmune diseases (e.g., type 1 diabetes, multiple sclerosis).\", \"Temporal alignment: The rise in autoimmune diseases (HY01-E1) post-1980 may not perfectly match the timeline of microbial exposure changes (e.g., antibiotic use, urbanization).\"], \"what_would_change_my_mind\": [\"Longitudinal studies tracking microbial exposure from birth to adulthood, with controls for confounders (diet, pollution, genetics), showing a dose-response relationship between microbial diversity and autoimmune disease risk.\", \"Intervention studies (e.g., randomized controlled trials of microbial exposure in early child"}', '2026-02-08 11:44:29.796624');
